 {"id": "franken_networkx-ndbndset", "title": "REVIEW: [MEDIUM] node_boundary returned list; nx returns set", "description": "nx.node_boundary returns a set of nodes incident to the boundary between nbunch1 and (optionally) nbunch2. The direct re-export of the Rust binding returned a plain list \u2014 callers doing set operations (``{x} == boundary``, ``boundary.issubset(...)``, intersection, union) silently broke. Wrap with set coercion in the Python wrapper.", "status": "closed", "priority": 3, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T19:00:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T19:00:00.000000000Z", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T19:00:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "Coerce to set", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
 {"id": "franken_networkx-bethedef", "title": "REVIEW: [HIGH] bethe_hessian_matrix default regularizer r differed from nx", "description": "nx's default regularizer is ``r = sum(d_i^2)/sum(d_i) - 1`` per Le & Levina 2015. fnx used ``r = max(sqrt(mean(degree)), 1.0)`` which is a different statistic, so any call without an explicit ``r=`` yielded a different Bethe Hessian matrix. On path(5) fnx's r was ~1.265 (diag 2.6, off-diag 1.265) while nx's r was 0.75 (diag 1.5625, off-diag 0.75). Callers using the default branch silently got wrong spectral-clustering intermediates. Fixed the default-r computation to mirror nx's formula. Non-default r still uses whatever the caller passes (matches nx too).", "status": "closed", "priority": 2, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T19:30:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T19:30:00.000000000Z", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T19:30:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "Match nx's r = sum(d^2)/sum(d)-1 formula", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
 {"id": "franken_networkx-eignstart", "title": "REVIEW: [HIGH] eigenvector_centrality raised TypeError on nstart= or weight= kwargs", "description": "The Rust _raw_eigenvector_centrality rejected ``nstart`` and ``weight`` with ``TypeError('franken_networkx currently only supports nstart=None and weight=None for eigenvector_centrality')``. nx accepts both \u2014 ``weight`` for weighted adjacency and ``nstart`` for custom power-iteration starting vectors. Delegate to nx whenever either is non-default; keep the Rust fast path for the common unweighted/no-nstart case. Verified parity on path(5) with uniform nstart, a weighted edge, and the karate default case.", "status": "closed", "priority": 2, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T19:30:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T19:30:00.000000000Z", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T19:30:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "Delegate when nstart or weight non-default", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
+{"id": "franken_networkx-tuttesig", "title": "REVIEW: [HIGH] tutte_polynomial signature required positional x,y; nx takes only G", "description": "nx.tutte_polynomial(G) returns a symbolic sympy polynomial in x, y. fnx's wrapper required numeric positional arguments ``tutte_polynomial(G, x, y)`` and evaluated the polynomial at that point, so drop-in calls like ``nx.tutte_polynomial(G)`` raised TypeError('missing 2 required positional arguments: x and y'). Made x, y default to None. When both are None, delegate to nx (returns sympy polynomial; raises ModuleNotFoundError if sympy unavailable, matching nx's behaviour). When both are provided, keep fnx's numeric deletion-contraction evaluator as an extension. Partial args (only one of x, y) now raise TypeError with a clear message.", "status": "closed", "priority": 2, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T20:00:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T20:00:00.000000000Z", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T20:00:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "Default x=y=None; delegate to nx for symbolic; retain numeric extension", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
